WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.677
A mixture is what you get when substances hang around
together without being chemically rebuilt into anything
new.

2
00:00:06.677 --> 00:00:17.752
Picture cereal and milk. The cereal is still cereal. The
milk is still milk. You could, with patience and a spoon,
fish every piece back out.

3
00:00:17.752 --> 00:00:25.087
A compound is different. In a compound, atoms of different
elements are chemically joined in a fixed arrangement.

4
00:00:25.087 --> 00:00:34.851
Water is not a loose pile of hydrogen and oxygen. It is a
new substance with its own properties, and no spoon will
un-join it.

5
00:00:34.851 --> 00:00:43.895
That gives us the big rule: mixtures can be pulled apart
with physical tricks. Compounds need a chemical reaction
to take apart.

6
00:00:43.895 --> 00:00:51.515
Some mixtures are obvious. Sand and pebbles. Paper clips
and rice. You can see the parts.

7
00:00:51.515 --> 00:01:04.024
Some hide well. Salt water looks like plain water, but
salt particles are spread all through it. A mixture that
looks uniform like this is called a solution.

8
00:01:04.024 --> 00:01:12.613
Dissolved does not mean gone. Stir sugar into water, taste
it, and the sweetness reports that the sugar is still in
there.

9
00:01:12.613 --> 00:01:26.650
Dissolving is a physical change: the sugar is spread out,
not rebuilt. Salt is soluble in water. Sand is insoluble -
it refuses to dissolve, and that refusal will come in

10
00:01:26.650 --> 00:01:34.399
Now for the fun part: getting mixtures apart. Chemists
pick a separation method by looking at properties.

11
00:01:34.399 --> 00:01:43.967
Different sizes? Use a sieve. Pebbles stay on top, sand
falls through. The holes only care about size.

12
00:01:43.967 --> 00:01:52.966
Insoluble solid in a liquid? Use a filter. Filter paper
catches sand from muddy water like a very fine net.

13
00:01:52.966 --> 00:02:02.209
But a filter will not remove dissolved salt from water.
Dissolved particles are far too small - they sail straight
through the paper.

14
00:02:02.209 --> 00:02:11.469
For salt water, use evaporation. Let the water leave as
vapour, and the salt is left behind as crystals, looking
slightly betrayed.

15
00:02:11.469 --> 00:02:22.635
Something magnetic in the mix? Use a magnet. It pulls iron
filings straight out of sand. It does nothing for rice,
because rice is not secretly metal.

16
00:02:22.635 --> 00:02:35.881
If a liquid is sitting above a settled solid, you can
sometimes pour the liquid off carefully. That is
decanting. Less precise than filtering, but a real method.

17
00:02:35.881 --> 00:02:50.544
For mixed inks or dyes, chemists use chromatography. On
paper, the colours travel different distances and spread
apart - a tiny race where the colours finally stop

18
00:02:50.544 --> 00:03:04.976
Sometimes you need a sequence. Take sand, salt, and iron
filings. Magnet out the iron. Add water to dissolve the
salt. Filter out the sand. Evaporate the water to get the

19
00:03:04.976 --> 00:03:14.081
Four steps, because the mixture offers four different
handles: magnetism, solubility, size, and evaporation.

20
00:03:14.081 --> 00:03:28.165
This is why there is no magic separation machine. A filter
is brilliant for muddy water and useless for dissolved
salt. A magnet is brilliant for iron and deeply

21
00:03:28.165 --> 00:03:40.956
One more solution fact: keep adding salt to water and
eventually no more will dissolve. The solution is
saturated - extra salt just sits at the bottom, waiting.

22
00:03:40.956 --> 00:03:49.613
Warmer water can usually dissolve more than cold water,
which is why sugar vanishes faster in hot tea than in iced
tea.

23
00:03:49.613 --> 00:04:00.460
So separation is a planning problem. Identify the parts,
list their properties, then pick the method that uses the
biggest difference between them.

24
00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:07.134
The separation question is always the same: what property
lets me pull these parts apart?
